Pattern 2: KMP (Knuth-Morris-Pratt)
KMP is the undisputed king of strict $O(N + M)$ matching. It guarantees you never move your text pointer backward.

1. The Concept: 
When a mismatch occurs, the naive approach resets the text pointer to where it started + 1. KMP looks at the characters it already matched and asks: "Is there a suffix in what I just matched that is also a prefix of the pattern?" It uses the LPS array to skip redundant checks.

2. Java Blueprint
Java
public int kmpSearch(String text, String pattern) {
    if (pattern.isEmpty()) return 0;
    
    int[] lps = buildLPS(pattern);
    int i = 0; // index for text
    int j = 0; // index for pattern
    
    while (i < text.length()) {
        if (pattern.charAt(j) == text.charAt(i)) {
            i++; j++;
        }
        
        if (j == pattern.length()) {
            return i - j; // Match found at index (i - j)
            // j = lps[j - 1]; // Uncomment if finding ALL occurrences
        } 
        else if (i < text.length() && pattern.charAt(j) != text.charAt(i)) {
            if (j != 0) {
                j = lps[j - 1]; // Fallback using LPS array
            } else {
                i++; // No fallback possible, move text pointer
            }
        }
    }
    return -1;
}

// Helper to build the Longest Proper Prefix/Suffix array
private int[] buildLPS(String pattern) {
    int[] lps = new int[pattern.length()];
    int len = 0; // length of previous longest prefix suffix
    int i = 1;
    
    while (i < pattern.length()) {
        if (pattern.charAt(i) == pattern.charAt(len)) {
            len++;
            lps[i] = len;
            i++;
        } else {
            if (len != 0) {
                len = lps[len - 1]; // Tricky part: backtrack len
            } else {
                lps[i] = 0;
                i++;
            }
        }
    }
    return lps;
}

3. Essential Interview Questions
Easy/Medium: Repeated Substring Pattern (LeetCode 459) - Math trick: If n % (n - lps[n - 1]) == 0, the string is formed by a repeating substring.
Hard: Shortest Palindrome (LeetCode 214) - Create a new string s + "#" + reverse(s). The last value of the LPS array of this new string tells you the longest palindromic prefix.
